                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1500" notAfter="1700">
                        <p>The binding was made for Henry VIII, and his librarian <persName key="person_14849374">John Leland</persName> wrote a title for the volume 
                           ('Vitæ illustrium virorum ...') and also a short 'Carmen Joannis Leylandi Londinensis', a comparison of Plutarch and Sulpicius 
                           Severus as biographers (fol. ii verso). 
                           The sides (only) of the old binding are inlaid in the brown leather cover of the latter part of the 17th century, and each bears within a border of 
                           gold ornament the arms and badges of the king with: DIEV: ET: MON: DROIT .:. REX: HENRICVS: VIII', and twice a crowned rose 
                           between K and H.: there is now an American cloth cover. Illustrations of the binding, with accounts of it, are in W. S. Brassington's <title>
                              <ref target="https://archive.org/details/b29353658/page/16/mode/2up">Historic Bindings in the Bodleian Library</ref></title>
                           (London, 1891, Pl. viii), and C. Davenport's <title><ref target="https://archive.org/details/gri_33125008106136/page/n22/mode/1up?q=gregory">
                              Royal English Bindings</ref></title> (London, 1896, Fig. 2)</p>
                     </binding>
